## Layer 3 — Jellyfin server settings

ProxyGate cannot control these — but the app SHOULD surface them as a
"Jellyfin optimization checklist" in the Known Applications page.
Show each item as a toggle with a status indicator that checks via the
Jellyfin API whether the setting is currently enabled.

### 3.1 Direct play — MOST IMPORTANT server setting

Direct play means Jellyfin sends the original file bytes directly to the client
with no processing. Zero CPU. Zero added latency. Playback starts in under 1 second.

Transcoding means Jellyfin re-encodes the file in real time. This adds:
- 2–10 seconds of startup delay while the transcode buffer fills
- Continuous CPU/GPU usage
- Seek lag (must re-start transcode from the nearest keyframe)

The goal is: **client plays direct whenever possible, transcode only as fallback.**

Settings in Jellyfin Admin → Playback:
  Allow media playback that requires transcoding: ON (keep as fallback)
  Allow video direct stream: ON
  Allow video direct play: ON
  Maximum allowed bitrate: 0 (unlimited) — CRITICAL, default 20Mbps blocks 4K

### 3.2 Hardware transcoding

When transcoding IS required (wrong codec, client can't handle HEVC, etc.),
hardware transcoding reduces startup lag from 5–10s to 1–2s and eliminates
the CPU bottleneck that causes stutter on concurrent streams.

Jellyfin Admin → Playback → Transcoding:

NVIDIA GPU (NVENC):
  Hardware acceleration: NVENC
  Enable hardware decoding for: H.264, HEVC, MPEG2, VC1, VP8, VP9, AV1
  Enable hardware encoding: ON
  NVENC options: Enable B-frames: ON, Enable lookahead: ON
  Preset: P4 (balanced — good quality, fast encode start)
  Tune: ll (low latency) for streaming

Intel GPU (Quick Sync / VAAPI on Linux):
  Hardware acceleration: VAAPI or QSV
  Enable hardware decoding: all codecs
  Low-power encoding: ON (uses less power, similar speed)
  Prefer OS-native DXVA2/D3D11VA on Windows

AMD GPU (VAAPI on Linux):
  Hardware acceleration: VAAPI
  Enable hardware decoding: H.264, HEVC, VP9

No GPU:
  Hardware acceleration: None
  Encoding threads: leave at 0 (auto — uses all cores)
  Enable throttle transcodes: ON (prevents runaway CPU if many streams start at once)

### 3.3 HLS segment size and transcode buffer

HLS (HTTP Live Streaming) is how Jellyfin delivers transcoded video.
It cuts the video into segments and sends them one at a time.

Jellyfin Admin → Playback → Transcoding:
  Segment length: 3 (seconds) — smaller segments = faster seek response
                                 default is 3, do NOT increase it
  Allow on-demand metadata-based seeking: ON — seeks within already-downloaded
                                              segments without re-requesting the server
  Transcode path: set to a fast SSD, NOT a network share or HDD

The transcode output directory should be on the FASTEST storage available,
separate from the media library. It is temp space only and can be cleared safely.

### 3.4 Remuxing preference

Remuxing = changing the container format (e.g. MKV → MP4) without re-encoding the video.
This is much faster than transcoding because the video and audio streams are copied as-is.
Remux startup time: ~300ms. Transcode startup time: 2–10s.

Jellyfin Admin → Playback:
  Allow video direct stream: ON — enables remux when codec is compatible but container is not

### 3.5 Network bandwidth setting

Jellyfin throttles its own output if the network setting is too low.

Jellyfin Admin → Playback:
  Maximum internet streaming bitrate: 0 (unlimited)
  Maximum LAN streaming bitrate: 0 (unlimited)

A 4K HDR HEVC stream at high bitrate requires 60–120 Mbps. If this is capped at
the old default of 20Mbps, 4K will always transcode down even if the client
can handle the original.

### 3.6 Codec priority order

Jellyfin Admin → Playback → Transcoding → Codec priority:
  Move H.264 and HEVC to the top of the preferred codec list.
  Modern clients (browsers, Apple TV, Roku, Fire TV) support H.264 natively for direct play.
  HEVC (H.265) is supported natively on Apple devices and newer smart TVs.
  AV1 — enable if your hardware supports it; newer clients handle it natively.

Priority order recommendation:
  1. H.264 (universal support, direct play on everything)
  2. HEVC/H.265 (direct play on Apple + newer TVs)
  3. AV1 (best compression, direct play on Chrome + Firefox + modern TVs)
  4. VP9 (fallback for older browsers)
  5. MPEG-4 (legacy fallback)

### 3.7 Subtitle rendering

Subtitles are a hidden source of forced transcoding.

Image-based subtitles (PGS, VOBSUB, DVB) CANNOT be streamed directly — Jellyfin
must burn them into the video via transcode, even if the video codec is otherwise
compatible for direct play. This turns a 300ms remux start into a 5–10s transcode.

Recommendations:
  Prefer text subtitle formats (SRT, ASS, SSA) in your media library when possible.
  Jellyfin Admin → Playback: Allow extraction of image-based subtitles: ON
    (Jellyfin converts PGS to text on first play — subsequent plays are direct)
  Install jellyfin-ffmpeg with subtitle support compiled in.

