## Layer 4 — Storage and network

### 4.1 Storage speed hierarchy

NVMe SSD > SATA SSD > HDD RAID > single HDD > network share

For the media library (read-only during streaming):
  Any disk type is fine for 1080p (reads ~40–100 Mbps sequential)
  4K HDR requires ~100–150 Mbps sustained reads — HDDs can handle this for 1–2 streams
  For 3+ concurrent 4K streams: SSD strongly recommended

For the transcode temp directory:
  Must be fast random write + fast random read (seek operations)
  NVMe SSD ideal. Never use a network share (NFS, SMB) for transcode temp.
  Location: /tmp/jellyfin-transcodes or a dedicated SSD partition

### 4.2 RAM as read cache (optional but impactful)

Linux page cache automatically caches recently-read files in free RAM.
If a movie is watched regularly it will be served from RAM (~microseconds) not disk (~milliseconds).

For servers with 32GB+ RAM:
  No configuration needed — Linux does this automatically.
  Ensure you are NOT using a swap file on the media drive (kills sequential reads).

Optional: use `vmtouch` to pin specific media files permanently in RAM:
  vmtouch -t /media/shows/popular-series/  # pin a whole series in RAM

### 4.3 LAN bandwidth

Streaming one 4K HDR HEVC file at original quality:
  Bitrate: 60–120 Mbps
  Per stream: needs 100Mbps reliable bandwidth between Jellyfin server and ProxyGate

Recommendations:
  Use wired Ethernet (Cat5e minimum, Cat6 preferred) between media server and router.
  Never use Wi-Fi for the media server — even Wi-Fi 6 has variable throughput.
  ProxyGate and Jellyfin server on the same switch = best latency (sub-1ms).

For multiple concurrent 4K streams: Gigabit switch required. 100Mbps switches will bottleneck.

### 4.4 Jumbo frames (advanced, optional)

Jumbo frames increase MTU from 1500 to 9000 bytes on LAN.
Each network packet carries 6× as much data, reducing the number of interrupts
and CPU overhead for large file transfers like video streaming.

Only effective if ALL devices on the path support it:
  Jellyfin server NIC: MTU 9000
  ProxyGate server NIC: MTU 9000
  All switches on the path: jumbo frames enabled

Linux: ip link set eth0 mtu 9000
Persistent: add MTU=9000 to the NetworkManager connection or /etc/systemd/network/

Do NOT enable if any device on the path does not support jumbo frames — it will
fragment packets and make performance WORSE.

